Let's write the fixed code:

```java
    protected int findWrapPos(String text, int width, int startPos)
    {
        int pos;
        
        // the line ends before the max wrap pos or a new line char found
        if (((pos = text.indexOf('\n', startPos)) != -1 && pos <= startPos + width)
                || ((pos = text.indexOf('\t', startPos)) != -1 && pos <= startPos + width))
        {
            return pos + 1;
        }
        else if (startPos + width >= text.length())
        {
            return -1;
        }


        // look for the last whitespace character before startPos+width
        pos = startPos + width;

        char c;

        while ((pos >= startPos) && ((c = text.charAt(pos)) != ' ')
                && (c != '\n') && (c != '\r'))
        {
            --pos;
        }

        // if we found it - just return
        if (pos > startPos)
        {
            return pos;
        }
        
        // if we didn't find one, simply chop at startPos+width
        pos = startPos + width;
        while ((pos < text.length()) && ((c = text.charAt(pos)) != ' ')
               && (c != '\n') && (c != '\r'))
        {
            ++pos;
        }        
        return pos == text.length() ? -1 : pos;
    }
```

Note: Changed `pos <= text.length()` to `pos < text.length()` in the forward while loop.

Also note: The original code had `pos <= text.length()` but also the return condition `pos == text.length() ? -1 : pos` is correct if we don't attempt charAt at length. So after fix, when pos reaches text.length(), the loop stops, and then it returns -1. That matches the original intent.

One more potential issue: In the forward scan, after loop exits, if we found a whitespace, pos will be the index of that whitespace. The original returns pos. That's fine.

